<HEAD>Monthly Review. SAMUEL HARRISON SMITH, SUBMITS TO THE PATRONAGE OF THE CITIZENS OF THE UNITED STATES, THE RE-PUBLICATION OF THE MONTHLY REVIEW, ENLARGED.</HEAD>
<P>IN &s;electing this work for the pre&s;s, the Publi&s;her's candor obliges him to &s;ay that views of a pecuniary com|plexion had a primary influence on his conduct; but his feelings will not permit him to withhold the de|claration that a con&s;ciou&s;ne&s;s of the many advantages at|tendant on its circulation, if it did not originate, at lea&s;t, fixed his wavering re&s;olution. Its &s;ub&s;ervience to the leading principles on which our pre&s;ent pro&s;perity depends, and on which alone our future well-being can be &s;ecured, renders it an object worthy of public regard. If the diffu&s;ion of the Monthly Review can be &s;hewn to carry with it the&s;e important benefits, the Printer cannot he&s;itate a moment in the a&s;&s;urance, that it will meet with a warm and general &s;upport. For the &s;atisfaction of tho&s;e who may not have an opportunity of recurring to the work it&s;elf, a &s;hort account of its nature, its tendency, and its execution, is pre&s;ented.</P>
<P>I. IT profe&s;&s;es to be a review of all the original publi|cations that appear in Great Britain, and &s;uch of tho&s;e written on the Continent as are deemed works of merit. In this review, the author's principles, talents, and infor|mation are te&s;ted by the rules of &s;cience and critici&s;m, a deci&s;ion is pronounced, which if equitably made, ei|ther holds forth his offspring to cordial patronage, or cold neglect. The reader of the Review is not dictated to by the writer of the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> and compelled <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 span">
<PB N="2" REF="026918_0256_0FD261D971379048">
to his opinion, through a deficiency of materials qualify|ing him to form a judgment him&s;elf; he is enabled to judge both of the merit of the original, and the ju&s;tice of the critici&s;m, by copious extracts, which are u&s;ually made from all works of an intere&s;ting nature.</P>
<P>IN the&s;e performances, information and critici&s;m are happily blended. To u&s;eful and improving narrative are added intere&s;ting argument and &s;pirited di&s;cu&s;&s;ion; form|ing &s;o plea&s;ing an a&s;&s;emblage as to command the lively attention even of tho&s;e who&s;e impatience revolts at the labour of peru&s;ing a lengthy, &s;y&s;tematic work. The review of any publication, may be con&s;idered, if the phra&s;e be allowed, as its kernel, presenting its hidden trea&s;ures, without condemning the reader to the labour of exploring them. No evidence can be more conclu&s;ive of the charms this periodical work po&s;&s;e&s;&s;es than the e&s;ti|mation in which it is held in England. This e&s;timation will be be&s;t under&s;tood by an acquaintance with the en|couragement it receives. This &s;urpa&s;&s;es that of any other i&s;&s;ue of the pre&s;s, except &s;uch as are intimately con|nected with religious duties.</P>
<P>II. IT is conducted with di&s;tingui&s;hed ability, and un|&s;haken impartiality. The liberal patronage which &s;u&s;|tains it, fo&s;ters the one, and in&s;ures the other. More than twenty thou&s;and di&s;intere&s;ted per&s;ons cannot be &s;up|po&s;ed to unite in the &s;teady &s;upport of any object, with|out that object being both laudable and de&s;irable. By an cxten&s;ive circulation and corre&s;pondent encouragement, the proprietors are enabled to command the talents of men di&s;tingui&s;hed for their acqui&s;itions in the &s;everal de|partments of &s;cience and literature. The generous re|ward which talents thus exerted receive, aided by that &s;prit of independence which knowledge ever in&s;pires, rai&s;e the writers for this work above tho&s;e paltry temp|tations which &s;o often corrupt mean and unenlightened minds. The&s;e remarks are &s;trengthened in the highe&s;t degree, by a clo&s;e attention to the manner in which this
<PB N="3" REF="026918_0257_0FD261EEA5F18040">
performance has actually been executed. Few reflec|tions have been ca&s;t upon it, and of the&s;e few, mo&s;t of them exhibit the traits of mortified dulne&s;s. Tho&s;e works which have received the la&s;h of &s;everity from the Reviewers, have almo&s;t univer&s;ally retreated into ob&s;curity, while &s;uch as have been crowned with the meed of prai&s;e, have gradually rai&s;ed their heads and flouri&s;hed, in &s;pite of prejudiced or intere&s;ted oppo&s;ition. It is not contended, that this has been an univer&s;al effect; but it is averred to have been a general one.</P>
<P>III. THE Monthly Review from its commencement to the pre&s;ent day, has uniformly aided and &s;upported the cau&s;e of civil and religious liberty. In times, when freedom of expre&s;&s;ion apparently approached the verge of de&s;truction, when oppo&s;ition to the infatuated coun|cils of Britain, drew forth the vengeance of government, and endangered the exi&s;tence of the patriot, the authors of this publication, in&s;tead of yielding to the power that menaced them, &s;ummoned to their cau&s;e all the energy of indignant truth, and thereby formed a barrier to that &s;ervile &s;ubmi&s;&s;ion which had begun to &s;pread it&s;elf among the people. During the American conte&s;t, they boldly pronounced the conduct of mini&s;ters to be replete with folly and depravity, and enjoyed the ultimate &s;atisfac|tion of beholding the nation pro&s;elytes to their &s;enti|ments. At the pre&s;ent cri&s;is, when in England liberty is in her la&s;t agonies, and &s;udden ruin threatens every man who dares to doubt the infallibility of the admi|ni&s;trators of her government, we ob&s;erve this work pre|&s;erving its wonted dignity: In &s;ome &s;mall degree, it is true, accommodating it&s;elf to the &s;pirit of the times, that prejudice may be more &s;ucce&s;sfully eradicated by appearing to yield to it. But never meanly applauding what rea&s;on mu&s;t condemn, never ba&s;ely courting the fa|vour of the powerful by panegyrizing their crimes: Avoiding the imputation of a ra&s;h intemperate zeal, at the &s;ame time that no &s;it occa&s;ion is &s;uffered to pa&s;s without a clear expo&s;ure of tho&s;e principles which con&s;titute the</P>
<P><PB N="4" REF="026918_0258_0FD261DBA43A1028">
THESE ob&s;ervations have been made in order to draw the attention of Americans to a work, which, on account of its extent and the variety of printing in its execution (almo&s;t every kind of letter occurring) requires an exten|&s;ive patronage to compen&s;ate the expences of conducting it. They might be enlarged to a much greater extent&mdash; but every per&s;on who&s;e curio&s;ity is awakened, will find no difficulty in obtaining &s;atisfaction by an in&s;pection of the work it&s;elf, as it is much read notwith&s;tanding the heavy charges of importation.</P>
<P>THE Printer has but two additional remarks to make. Should that encouragement be received which the work is entitled to, he looks forward to the period as not a remote one, in which the publication &s;hall receive an acce&s;&s;ion of value, by a review of &s;uch original works as appear among our&s;elves. &mdash; The reduced price which the follow|ing terms fix, below that of the Engli&s;h edition, as well as the early and regular manner in which the American edition will be printed, &s;hould be influential induce|ments, added to others too obvious to be mentioned, to give a preference of our own manufactory to any foreign one.</P>
